<article>
    <h1>IN&#xAD;DULGE IN THAI CUI&#xAD;SINE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201222/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-22"><time>2020-12-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TRAVEL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>No mat­ter your bud­get, the salty, spicy, sour and sweet flavours of Thai cui­sine of­fers some­thing to whet your ap­petite. At hawker cen­tres and cof­fee shops is­land­wide, you can get a fra­grant plate of Thai pineap­ple fried rice or pad thai for un­der $6.</p>
    <p>If you are hun­gry, Suki-Suki Thai Hot Pot has a ha­lal­cer­ti­fied all-you-can-eat Thai hot pot buf­fet at HomeTeamNS Khatib. Prices start from $17.90 an adult for lunch from Mon­days to Thurs­days.</p>
    <p>The restau­rant’s vi­brant, Thai-in­spired in­te­rior is matched by warm hos­pi­tal­ity.</p>
    <p>Its six au­then­tic Thai soup bases – in­clud­ing tom yum soup, sweet basil chicken soup and khao soi broth, a north­ern Thai co­conut curry soup akin to laksa – pair per­fectly with the large va­ri­ety of in­gre­di­ents, such as thinly sliced fresh beef, chicken, mush­rooms and tofu.</p>
    <p>Tip: the house­made jaew sauce is best for dip­ping grilled meat, while the spicy and sour seafood sauce goes best with tiger prawns and dory fish.</p>
    <p>Even in Sin­ga­pore, you can dine like Thai roy­alty at Sabai Fine Thai on the Bay, lo­cated at Cus­toms House.</p>
    <p>It is known for curry dishes such as gang bpet yang pol­la­mai ($30.50, above right), which com­prises red or green curry with roasted duck, co­conut cream, sweet basil leaves and sea­sonal fresh fruits. Each mouth­ful is a burst of de­li­cious flavour.</p>
    <p>Sabai’s chefs come from all over Thai­land, such as Chi­ang Rai in the north, Chaiya­phum in the north-east and Nakhon Si Tham­marat in the south.</p>
    <p>They are happy to whip up Thai street food dishes from th­ese lo­cales – such as som tum pu plara, which is pa­paya salad with salted crab and fer­mented fish; and kanom jeen nam ngiaw, north­ern-style rice noo­dles with spicy pork and to­mato broth – upon re­quest, as long as they have the in­gre­di­ents.</p>

